"""
MKT Original Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 44–46
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-ezekiel-44-46-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ezekiel.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json (nasi, terumah, kavod, etc.)
- BDB and HALOT for key terms

Key decisions in this range:
- 44:1-3 east gate: YHWH's entry seals the gate; only the nasi eats there
- 44:28 'I am their inheritance': YHWH as the priests' portion echoes Num 18:20
- 45:9 direct address to princes: covenant justice demand still applies in the new order
- 46:16-18 inalienable tribal inheritance: echoes jubilee legislation from Lev 25
- nasi (prince) used throughout rather than melek (king) — intentional Ezekielian distinction
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_ORIGINAL = {
"44": {
    "1": '<p>The visionary guide brings Ezekiel to the outer east gate of the sanctuary. This is the same east gate through which the glory of YHWH departed (10:19; 11:23) and returned (43:1-4). The gate\'s future status is now revealed — it will remain sealed permanently, its closing serving as a permanent memorial to the divine entry.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>sagar yihyeh lo yippatach</strong> (\'it shall be shut; it shall not be opened\'): the absolute permanence of the closure established through doubled negative construction. <em>Ve\'ish lo-yavo vo ki YHWH Elohei Yisrael ba bo</em> (\'and no one shall enter by it, because YHWH the God of Israel entered by it\'): the gate sealed by divine entry is thereby permanently reserved for YHWH. The logic is that of holiness by contact — the gateway touched by the divine presence becomes permanently sacred and off-limits to ordinary use.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>hanasi hanasi hu yeshev-bo</strong> (\'the prince, the prince — he shall sit in it\'): the emphatic double title. <em>Nasi</em> (prince) — Ezekiel\'s deliberate choice throughout chapters 40-48 to avoid <em>melek</em> (king). The kings had profaned YHWH\'s sanctuary (43:7-9); in the restored order the human leader has a different title and a different relationship to the sacred space. The prince may enter by the vestibule and eat a covenantal meal in the gateway — a unique privilege marking his mediating role.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>vayavi\'eni derekh sha\'ar hatzafon el-pnei habayit</strong> (\'and he brought me by the way of the north gate to the front of the house\'): Ezekiel is repositioned for a new view. <strong>va\'ereh vehinneh male kavod-YHWH et-beit YHWH</strong> (\'I looked and behold, the glory of YHWH filled the house of YHWH\'): the <em>kavod</em> (glory) that departed in chapters 10-11 is now fully resident in the restored temple. Ezekiel\'s face-down response mirrors his response to the initial glory vision (1:28; 3:23).</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>sim libecha</strong> (\'set your heart/mind\'): <em>sim lev</em> (to direct attention, take note) — the same idiom used in 40:4 at the beginning of the temple tour. YHWH instructs Ezekiel to pay careful attention to all the ordinances and laws of the house — both the exits and entrances (<em>kol-motza\'ei hammiqdash</em>) and all the regulations (<em>kol-Torah hammiqdash</em>). The emphasis on careful observation prepares for the detailed priestly legislation that follows.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>ve\'amarta el-meri el-beit Yisrael</strong> (\'and say to the rebellious house of Israel\'): the oracle is directed to the rebellious house — the term <em>meri</em> (rebellious) was Ezekiel\'s epithet for Israel from the beginning (2:3, 5-8; 3:26-27). Even in the context of the restoration vision, the audience is reminded of the identity that made the departure of the glory necessary. The restoration is not earned but gracious.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>behavi\'achem bnei-neichar arelei-lev va\'aralei basar</strong> (\'when you brought foreigners, uncircumcised of heart and uncircumcised of flesh\'): the double uncircumcision — of heart and body. <em>Ben-neichar</em> (foreigner) — specifically a foreign national, not the <em>ger</em> (resident alien) who could be incorporated into the covenant. <em>Aral-lev</em> (uncircumcised of heart): the spiritual-moral category; <em>aral-basar</em> (uncircumcised of flesh): the physical-covenant mark. Deuteronomy 10:16 calls for heart-circumcision alongside physical circumcision; Ezekiel requires both for sanctuary access.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>velo shemartem mishmeret qodoshai</strong> (\'and you have not kept the charge of my holy things\'): <em>shameret</em> (charge/keeping/guard-duty) — the specific custodial responsibility of sanctuary service. Israel appointed others to perform the duties they should have done themselves. The specific failure named: outsiders in the sanctuary. The result is the profaning of YHWH\'s covenant — <em>lehafar et-briti</em>.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>koh amar Adonai YHWH kol-ben-neichar aral-lev va\'aral-basar lo-yavo el-miqdashi</strong> (\'thus says the Lord YHWH: no foreigner, uncircumcised of heart and uncircumcised of flesh, shall enter my sanctuary\'): the absolute exclusion rule for the new temple. The doubling of the condition (heart AND flesh) distinguishes the foreigner from those who might have physical circumcision without covenantal allegiance, or covenantal allegiance without the covenant sign.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>ki im-haleviyim asher-rachaqu me\'alai</strong> (\'but the Levites who went far from me\'): the Levites who participated in Israel\'s apostasy — who served at the <em>gillulim</em> (idols) when Israel went astray — receive a demoted status in the restored order. <em>Venasa\'u avontam</em> (\'they will bear their iniquity\'): their punishment is the loss of priestly status. They retain temple service but not altar ministry — a permanent consequence of their historical infidelity.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>meshartim babayit</strong> (\'serving in the house\'): the Levites\' reduced role — gatekeepers (<em>she\'arim hasha\'ar</em>), temple attendants (<em>meshartim et-habayit</em>), slaughtering the burnt offering and sacrifice for the people. They serve the people but not directly at the altar of YHWH. <em>Hem ya\'amdu lifneihem leshartam</em> (\'they shall stand before them to serve them\'): the preposition <em>lifneihem</em> (before them = the people) rather than <em>lifnei YHWH</em> (before YHWH) marks the demotion.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>ya\'an asher sher\'tu otam lifnei gilluleihem</strong> (\'because they served them before their idols\'): the <em>gillulim</em> again — the contemptuous dung-word for idols. The Levites ministered to Israel in the idolatrous context, facilitating rather than opposing the apostasy. <em>Vehayah leVet Yisrael lemikshol avon</em> (\'and became a stumbling block of iniquity to the house of Israel\'): the Levites who were supposed to prevent stumbling became the stumbling block.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>velo yigshu elai lechahanen li</strong> (\'and they shall not draw near to me to minister as priests to me\'): the <em>nagash</em> (draw near) vocabulary of priestly approach is denied to the apostate Levites. <em>Likol-qodshai</em> (\'to any of my holy things\'): exclusion from the entire realm of direct sacred ministry. They retain <em>some</em> temple function but not the constitutive function — the approach to YHWH in priestly mediation. <em>Venasu klimatam uveto\'avotam asher asu</em> (\'they shall bear their shame and their abominations which they committed\').</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>unatati otam shomrei mishmeret habayit</strong> (\'and I will make them keepers of the charge of the house\'): the specific role assigned to the demoted Levites — custodial maintenance. <em>Lekhol-avodat</em> (\'for all the service\'): the full range of support and maintenance tasks, but not the altar service. The Levitical demotion is not expulsion but reassignment — they remain in the covenant community but with different responsibilities that reflect the permanent mark of their historical infidelity.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>uhakohanim haleviyim bnei Tzadok</strong> (\'but the priests, the Levites, the sons of Zadok\'): the contrast clause — <em>asher shamru et-mishmeret miqdashi</em> (\'who kept the charge of my sanctuary\'). The sons of Zadok maintained their priestly faithfulness during Israel\'s apostasy. <em>Hem yiqrevu elai lesharteni</em> (\'they shall draw near to me to serve me\'): the same <em>nagash</em> (draw near) that was denied to the apostate Levites is now granted to the faithful line. Access to the divine presence is the mark and reward of fidelity.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>hem yavo\'u el-miqdashi</strong> (\'they shall enter my sanctuary\'): the sons of Zadok as the full priests of the restored temple. <em>Ve\'hemah yiqrevu el-shulchani lesharteni</em> (\'and they shall approach my table to serve me\'): the \'table of YHWH\' — the altar as dining table. The metaphor of divine hospitality expressed in the altar-table imagery appears in Ezekiel 41:22 and 44:16; YHWH as host, the priests as servants of the table, Israel as the guests. <em>Veshemru et-mishmarti</em> (\'they shall keep my charge\').</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>uvevo\'am el-sha\'are hechatzer hapnimit bigdei pishtim yilbashu</strong> (\'when they enter the gates of the inner court, linen garments they shall wear\'): <em>pishtim</em> (linen/flax) — the priestly material prescribed since Exodus 28:39-42. Wool is explicitly forbidden in v.17b: <em>lo ya\'aleh alehem tzemer</em> (\'wool shall not come up on them while serving\'). The reason given in v.18 — \'so that they do not sweat\' — reflects the purity concern about bodily secretion in the sacred space.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>pea\'rei pishtim yihyu al-rosham</strong> (\'linen headcoverings shall be on their heads\'): <em>pe\'er</em> (turban/headcovering) — the priestly head covering. <em>Umiknesei-pishtim yihyu al-motneihem</em> (\'linen breeches/undergarments shall be on their waists\'): complete linen from head to waist. <em>Lo yachgeru bayya\'</em> (\'they shall not gird themselves with anything causing sweat\'): the bodily integrity requirement — the priestly body in sacred service must not produce the secretion associated with labor and physical exertion.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>ubetzetam el-hechatzer hachitzonah</strong> (\'when they go out to the outer court\'): the transition from holy to common space requires a change of garments. <em>Ufishtenu bigdeihem asher-yeshartam bam</em> (\'they shall put off the linen garments in which they have been serving\'): two sets of garments — one for the inner court (holy), one for the outer court (common). <em>Levelo-yequaddesh et-ha\'am bevigdeihem</em> (\'lest they consecrate/sanctify the people with their garments\'): holiness is contagious — the sacred garments can transfer sanctity to ordinary people who contact them, requiring a buffer between the holy and common realms.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>verosham lo yegale\'chu</strong> (\'and their heads they shall not shave\'): the prohibition on priestly shaving of the head (cf. Lev 21:5). <em>Vefara lo yeshallachu</em> (\'and they shall not let their hair grow wild/loose\'): the priest must not adopt the unkempt hair of the mourner or the Nazirite-like long growth. <em>Kasom yiksemu et-ra\'sheihem</em> (\'trimming they shall trim their heads\'): the middle path — neither shaved nor uncontrolled, regularly trimmed. The priest\'s body itself is regulated as part of sacred service.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>veyayin lo yishteh kol-kohen bevo\'am el-hechatzer hapnimit</strong> (\'and no priest shall drink wine when they enter the inner court\'): the alcohol prohibition in sacred service from Leviticus 10:9 (where the context is Nadab and Abihu\'s disastrous unauthorized fire — perhaps connected to intoxication). The inner court is the highest zone of sacred proximity; full cognitive clarity is required for service there.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>ve\'almana ugershusha lo-yiqchu lahem lenashim</strong> (\'and a widow or a divorcée they shall not take as wives for themselves\'): the stricter priestly marriage code. <em>Ki im-betulot mizera beit Yisrael</em> (\'but only virgins from the seed of the house of Israel\'): and widows of priests (<em>ve\'ha\'almana asher tihyeh almana mikohen yiqachu</em>). The high priest\'s restriction from Leviticus 21:14 is applied more broadly to all priests in the new temple order — the priestly family\'s purity reflecting the sanctuary\'s higher holiness.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>ve\'et-ami yoruu bein qodesh lechol</strong> (\'and my people they shall teach between holy and common\'): the core priestly teaching function — <em>havdalah</em> (distinction, separation), the ability to distinguish and communicate the difference between sacred and ordinary. <em>Uvein-tame utahor yori\'um</em> (\'and between clean and unclean they shall teach them\'): the full range of purity distinctions that structure Levitical religion. The priests as teachers of the sacred/common and clean/unclean distinctions is the foundational purpose of the priestly class (cf. Lev 10:10-11; Deut 33:10; Mal 2:7).</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>val-riv hemah ya\'amdu lishpot</strong> (\'and in a dispute they shall stand to judge\'): the priests as civil judges in cases of dispute. <em>Bemishpatai yishpetahu</em> (\'according to my ordinances they shall judge\'): YHWH\'s Torah as the legal code for the priestly court. <em>Ve\'et-torotai vechukotai bechol-mo\'adai yishmoru</em> (\'and my instruction and statutes at all my festivals they shall observe\'): the priestly role of legal, liturgical, and educational mediation fully described.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>ve\'el-met adam lo yavo litame\'</em> (\'and for a dead person he shall not come to be defiled\'): corpse impurity — the most severe level of uncleanness in Levitical law (Num 19). Only for the closest relatives — father, mother, son, daughter, brother, or unmarried sister — may a priest contract corpse impurity. <em>Ve\'im-lev lav yitamma\'\'u</em> (\'but for these they may defile themselves\'): the family exception to the general priestly prohibition on corpse contact.</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>ve\'achar taharo shiv\'at yamim yisperu-lo</strong> (\'and after his purification, seven days they shall count for him\'): the seven-day purification period after corpse defilement (Num 19:11-14). The counting begins the purification process — time as the healing mechanism within the purity system. <em>Veyom tiharto</em> (\'on the day of his cleansing\'): a fixed point after which priestly service can resume.</p>',
    "27": '<p><strong>uveyom bo\'o el-haQodesh</strong> (\'and on the day he enters the holy place\'): the reintegration offering. <em>El-hechatzer hapnimit lesharet baQodesh</em> (\'to the inner court to minister in the holy place\'): on the day the purified priest returns to full duty, he must offer a <em>chatat</em> (sin offering). The purification process is not merely the passage of time but requires a priestly sacrifice to restore full sacred access.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>uhayetah lahem lenachala ani nachalatam</strong> (\'and it shall be their inheritance — I am their inheritance\'): the most theologically charged verse in the priestly legislation. <em>Ani nachalatam</em> (\'I am their inheritance\') echoes Numbers 18:20 (\'I am your portion and your inheritance among the Israelites\') and the Levitical principle from Joshua 13:14 that YHWH himself is the Levitical inheritance. <em>Ve\'achuzah lo-titenu lahem beYisrael</em> (\'and possession you shall not give them among Israel\'): the priests receive no land — YHWH is their land.</p>',
    "29": '<p><strong>hamincha vehacha\'tat veha\'asham hemah yocheluhu</strong> (\'the grain offering, the sin offering, and the guilt offering — they shall eat them\'): the priestly portion from the sacrificial system. The three offerings eaten by priests at the sanctuary represent YHWH\'s provision for their physical needs. <em>Vechol-cherem beYisrael lahem yihyeh</em> (\'and every dedicated/devoted thing in Israel shall belong to them\'): <em>cherem</em> (dedicated thing) — items vowed or devoted to YHWH become priestly property.</p>',
    "30": '<p><strong>vere\'shit kol-bikkurei kol ukhol-terumah mikol</strong> (\'and the best of all the first-fruits of all, and every offering of all\'): the first-fruits (<em>bikkurim</em>) and contributions (<em>terumah</em>) belong to the priests. <em>Re\'shit arissoteichem titenu lakohen</em> (\'the first portion of your dough you shall give to the priest\'): even the dough-offering (<em>arisah</em> = dough, perhaps the first bread from the millstone) is priestly. <em>Lehaniach berakhah el-beitecha</em> (\'to bring blessing upon your house\'): the connection between giving first-fruits and receiving blessing — the economic order of worship sustains both priests and worshippers.</p>',
    "31": '<p><strong>kol-nevela uterefah min-ha\'of umin-habehemah lo yochlu hakohanim</strong> (\'all carcass or torn animal — whether bird or beast — the priests shall not eat\'): the standard Levitical prohibition on eating animals that die naturally or are killed by predators (Lev 22:8). The priests must not eat from death; their food must come through proper slaughter. This closes the priestly code of chapter 44 — the priest\'s complete separation from the unclean, the common, and death itself, sustained by YHWH\'s own provision as their inheritance.</p>'
},
"45": {
    "1": '<p><strong>uvehapilchem et-ha\'aretz benachala tarimu terumah laYHWH</strong> (\'and when you divide the land by lot as an inheritance, you shall set apart an offering for YHWH\'): <em>terumah</em> (offering/contribution/portion set apart) — literally \'that which is lifted up\' (<em>rum</em>, to rise). The sacred district is conceptually \'lifted\' from the surrounding land as the part dedicated to YHWH. <em>Qodesh hi</em> (\'it is holy\'): the designation of the entire district as sacred space, not merely the inner sanctuary.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>yihyeh min-zeh lamiqdash</strong> (\'this shall be for the sanctuary\'): the precise allocation of the sacred area. <em>Chamesh me\'ot b\'chamesh me\'ot ravia\'</em> (\'five hundred by five hundred — a square\'): the perfect square of the inner sanctuary precinct, already noted in 40:47. <em>Vachamishim amah migrash lo saviv</em> (\'and fifty cubits of open space around it\'): a buffer zone of unoccupied land surrounding the sanctuary compound — both for visual separation and practical protective distance.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The measured sacred district contains both the sanctuary and the priestly quarters (<em>lishkat hakohanim</em>). The sanctuary is embedded within the priestly territory — the priests literally dwell around their liturgical center. The spatial arrangement makes theological sense: those who serve the sanctuary should live in proximity to it, physically expressing the covenant of sacred service.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>qodesh hu min-ha\'aretz</strong> (\'it is holy — from/of the land\'): the land itself is categorized as holy by allocation. <em>Likohanim mesharte hammiqdash</em> (\'for the priests who minister at the sanctuary\'): the allocation is functional — the land serves those who serve the house. <em>Vemakom levatehem</em> (\'and a place for their houses\'): the priests\' domestic life is embedded within the sacred district — no separation between priestly home and priestly work.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>vachamisha esrim elef orech vachamisha asar elef rochav</strong> (\'twenty-five thousand long and fifteen thousand wide\'): the Levitical portion, somewhat smaller than the priestly portion. <em>Laleviyim meshartei habayit</em> (\'to the Levites, the servants of the house\'): the Levites\' district adjacent to the priestly district — the same spatial theology: those who serve the sanctuary live near it. <em>Achuzzat arim lahem</em> (\'possession of cities for them\'): the Levitical cities tradition from Numbers 35 continued in the new order.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>va\'achuzzat ha\'ir titenu</strong> (\'and the possession of the city you shall give\'): the city district — distinct from both the priestly/Levitical sacred section and the prince\'s section. <em>Chamesh elef rochav vachamisha ve\'esrim elef orech</em>: the city\'s dimensions. <em>Kol beit Yisrael</em> (\'for all the house of Israel\'): the city is communal property belonging to the whole covenant community, not to a tribe or the priestly class. The egalitarian city-portion is a structural covenant provision for all Israel.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>velanasi mize umize lterumah haQodesh ulachuzzat ha\'ir</strong> (\'and for the prince — on both sides of the sacred offering and the city property\'): the prince\'s land flanks the sacred and city districts on both sides (east and west). The spatial arrangement is theologically significant: the prince does not own the sacred center but flanks it as its guardian. <em>Umefaat yam yama umipaat qedma qedma</em> (\'from the western border to the sea, and from the eastern border to the east\'): the prince\'s territory extends to the actual borders of the land.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>ba\'aretz yihyeh-lo achuzzah beYisrael</strong> (\'in the land he shall have as property in Israel\'): the prince is guaranteed a specific territorial portion — he is not to be landless like the priests (44:28). <em>Velo-yonu od nasai et-ami</em> (\'and my princes shall no longer oppress my people\'): the specific prohibition on the kind of land-confiscation that characterized the Israelite monarchy (1 Kgs 21, Naboth\'s vineyard; cf. Isa 5:8; Mic 2:2). <em>Ve\'et-ha\'aretz yitenu leBeit Yisrael leshivteihem</em> (\'and the land they shall give to the house of Israel according to their tribes\').</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>rav-lachem nesi\'ei Yisrael</strong> (\'enough, O princes of Israel!\'): a direct, urgent address — <em>rav-lachem</em> is the strong rebuke used by Moses to the Levites in Numbers 16:3. <em>Chamas va\'shod hasiru</em> (\'remove violence and oppression!\'): the same charge against the rulers from 22:27 and 34:2-4. Even within the restoration vision, the priestly legislation addresses the princes with the covenant demand for justice. <em>Ve\'asitem mishpat utzedaqah</em> (\'and do justice and righteousness\'): the standard prophetic doublet for comprehensive covenant faithfulness.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>mozenei tzedeq ve\'efat tzedeq uvat tzedeq yihyeh lachem</strong> (\'honest scales and an honest ephah and an honest bath shall be yours\'): the three instruments of honest commerce: <em>moznayim</em> (scales, for weighing), <em>ephah</em> (dry measure), and <em>bat</em> (liquid measure). <em>Tzedeq</em> (honest/just) — the adjective that attaches to all three: the covenant requirement for commercial integrity drawn directly from Leviticus 19:35-36.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>ha\'efah ve\'habat tochen echad yihyeh lahem</strong> (\'the ephah and the bath — one standard they shall have\'): the standardization of the dry and liquid measures at the same volume. <em>Liset ma\'aser ha\'chomer</em> (\'to contain a tenth of a homer\'): the homer (<em>chomer</em>, a donkey-load) as the base unit, with the ephah and bath each being a tenth of it. The standardization eliminates the possibility of using different measures for buying and selling — a common form of ancient economic fraud.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>vehasheqel esrim gerah</strong> (\'and the shekel — twenty gerahs\'): the standard shekel weight defined. <em>Esrim sheqalim chamisha ve\'esrim sheqalim asarah vacha\'mishah sheqalim hamaneh yihyeh lachem</em> (\'twenty shekels, twenty-five shekels, fifteen shekels — the maneh shall be yours\'): the maneh = 60 shekels total (20+25+15). The standardization of weights is a covenant-justice requirement: dishonest weights are explicitly condemned in Leviticus 19:35-36 and Proverbs 11:1; 16:11; 20:23.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>zot haterumah asher tarimu</strong> (\'this is the offering that you shall contribute\'): the specified contribution rates. <em>Shishit ha\'eifah mikhomer hachittim</em> (\'a sixth of an ephah from a homer of wheat\'): one-sixtieth — a tithe on a tithe. The mathematical precision of the sacred contributions reflects the careful accounting of covenant obligations. The people\'s contribution to the prince funds the public worship that the prince is obligated to provide for the whole community.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>vechoq hashemen habat hashemen</strong> (\'and the ordained amount of oil — the bath of oil\'): the oil contribution rates. <em>Ma\'aser habat min-hakkor</em> (\'a tenth of a bath from the kor\'): the kor = 10 baths, so the tithe is one bath per kor. The careful layering of measurements (kor, bath, homer, ephah) establishes a consistent system of sacred contributions based on standardized measure.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>vesheh-achat min-hatzon</strong> (\'and one sheep from the flock\'): the animal contribution — one sheep per two hundred from the watered pastures of Israel. <em>Leminchah ulelolah ulshelamim</em> (\'for grain offering and burnt offering and peace offering\'): the three primary categories of sacrifice funded by these contributions. <em>Lechapper alehem</em> (\'to make atonement for them\'): the whole sacrificial system serves the atonement function — maintaining the community\'s covenant access to YHWH.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>kol-ha\'am ha\'aretz yihyu el-haterumah hazot</strong> (\'all the people of the land shall be involved in this contribution\'): the communal nature of the sacred contribution — it is not merely an individual religious duty but a collective provision for the national worship system. <em>El-hanasi beYisrael</em> (\'for the prince in Israel\'): the people fund the prince\'s obligatory offerings, and the prince provides the national worship. The economic triangle — people → prince → sanctuary → people — structures the covenant community\'s liturgical life.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>ve\'al-hanasi yihyeh ha\'olot vehamminchah vehanasekh</strong> (\'and upon the prince shall be the burnt offerings and the grain offerings and the drink offerings\'): the prince\'s specific liturgical obligations — funding all the burnt offerings, grain offerings, drink offerings, sin offerings, and peace offerings for national festivals, Sabbaths, new moons, and set times. <em>Lechapper bead beit Yisrael</em> (\'to make atonement for the house of Israel\'): the prince\'s role is ultimately intercessory — his funding of worship maintains the national relationship with YHWH.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>koh amar Adonai YHWH barishon be\'echad lachodesh</strong> (\'thus says the Lord YHWH: in the first month, on the first day of the month\'): the priestly calendar begins. The year-opening purification offering — taking a bull without blemish (<em>par ben-baqar tamim</em>) for the sin offering. <em>Vechitta et-hammiqdash</em> (\'and you shall purify the sanctuary\'): <em>chitta</em> (Piel of <em>chata\'</em>, to purify/decontaminate) — the sanctuary itself requires regular purification, not because YHWH is polluted but because the accumulated impurities of the worshipping community need periodic liturgical cleansing.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>velaqach hakohen middam hachatta\'t</strong> (\'and the priest shall take some of the blood of the sin offering\'): the blood application ritual — applying the sin-offering blood to the doorposts, the four corners of the altar ledge, and the doorposts of the inner court gate. The blood marks the sacred threshold as under the protection of the atonement sacrifice, extending the cleansing function beyond the altar itself to the entire sanctuary boundary.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>veken ta\'aseh beshiv\'ah lachodesh me\'ish shogeg ume\'peti</strong> (\'and so you shall do on the seventh of the month for those who sin unintentionally and for those who are naive\'): the seventh-day purification ritual. <em>Shogeg</em> (one who sins inadvertently/unintentionally) — the category of non-deliberate sin covered by the Levitical purification system (Num 15:27-29). The twice-yearly purification (first and seventh days of the first month) covers the accumulated unintentional sins of the community.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>barishon bearba\'ah asar yom lachodesh yihyeh lachem haPesach</strong> (\'in the first month on the fourteenth day shall be the Passover for you\'): the restoration-temple Passover — on the same date as the original (Ex 12:6). <em>Chametz</em> (leaven) absent from the festival — <em>shiv\'at yamim matzot ye\'achel</em> (\'seven days of unleavened bread shall be eaten\'). The Passover as the foundational covenant-memorial is maintained unchanged in the new temple order — the Exodus remains the paradigmatic salvation event even in the eschatological restoration.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>ve\'asah hanasi bayom hahu</strong> (\'and the prince shall prepare on that day\'): the prince\'s Passover role — providing a bull as a sin offering for himself and all the people. The prince\'s intercession on behalf of the whole community is explicit: he atones for himself (<em>bado</em>) and for all the people (<em>bead kol-am ha\'aretz</em>). The priestly-intercessory dimension of the nasi function is most visible at the great festivals.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>ushiv\'at yamim ha\'chag ya\'aseh olah laYHWH</strong> (\'and for seven days of the feast he shall prepare a burnt offering for YHWH\'): the Passover week offerings — seven bulls and seven rams daily, without blemish (<em>tamim</em>). <em>Lechatta\'t sa\'ir izim echad layom</em> (\'and for a sin offering a male goat daily\'): the goat sin offering maintained throughout the festival week. The magnitude of the Passover offering — seven perfect bulls and seven perfect rams daily for seven days plus a goat — reflects the weight of the atonement the festival is accomplishing for the whole community.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>uminchah efah lapar ve\'efah la\'ayil</strong> (\'and as a grain offering an ephah for the bull and an ephah for the ram\'): the proportionate grain accompaniment to the animal sacrifices. <em>Vehin shemen la\'efah</em> (\'and a hin of oil per ephah\'): the oil portion. The precision of the measurements reflects the covenant exactitude — the liturgical calendar is not improvised but ordered according to divine specification.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>beshivi\'i bechamisha asar yom lachodesh bechag</strong> (\'in the seventh month, on the fifteenth day of the month, at the feast\'): the Feast of Booths (<em>Sukkot</em>), though not named as such. <em>Ke\'eleh ya\'aseh shiv\'at hayamim</em> (\'according to these he shall do for seven days\'): the symmetry between Passover (first month, 14th) and Booths (seventh month, 15th) is maintained — two seven-day festivals with identical offerings, creating a liturgical year structured around the two great redemptive memories (Exodus from Egypt / wilderness wandering). <em>Kachatta\'t ke\'olah ukhaminchah vekhasshamen</em>: all offerings identical to Passover.</p>'
},
"46": {
    "1": '<p><strong>koh amar Adonai YHWH sha\'ar hechatzer hapnimit</strong> (\'thus says the Lord YHWH: the gate of the inner court\'): the gate regulations for the east gate of the inner court (not the outer east gate of 44:1-2). The six working days/two exceptional days principle: <em>sheshet yamei hama\'aseh yisager</em> (\'on the six days of work it shall be shut\') and <em>veyom hashabbat yippatach</em> (\'but on the day of Sabbath it shall be opened\') — the Sabbath and New Moon as the days of open access to the inner court.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>uva hanasi derekh ulam hasha\'ar mibachutz</strong> (\'and the prince shall enter by the vestibule of the gate from outside\'): the prince\'s specific entry route. <em>Ve\'amad al-mezuzat hasha\'ar</em> (\'he shall stand at the doorpost of the gate\'): the prince as a liminal figure — standing at the threshold between common and sacred space. He does not enter the sanctuary but stands at its gate. The priests prepare his offerings; he oversees from the threshold. His Sabbath and New Moon worship is described in detail (vv. 4-7).</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>vehishtachavu am ha\'aretz petach hasha\'ar hazeh</strong> (\'and the people of the land shall worship at the entrance of that gate\'): the congregation worships at the outer gate while the prince stands at the inner gate. The concentric model of sacred access: prince closer to the inner court than the people, but neither entering the sanctuary itself. The spatial theology of access matches covenantal proximity: the people gather at the outer perimeter of sacred space.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>vehha\'olah asher-yaqrib hanasi laYHWH beyom hashabbat</strong> (\'and the burnt offering that the prince shall bring to YHWH on the Sabbath day\'): six lambs and a ram without blemish — the Sabbath offering in the new temple order. The Sabbath offering increases dramatically from the Torah\'s two lambs (Num 28:9-10) to six lambs plus a ram — the eschatological intensification of Sabbath worship. <em>Tamim</em> (without blemish) governs all the animals.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>vehamminchah la\'ayil</strong> (\'and the grain offering for the ram\'): the grain accompaniment. <em>Ve\'likhvasim minchah matnat yado</em> (\'and for the lambs, a grain offering as his hand gives freely\'): <em>matnat yado</em> (the gift of his hand) — a freewill element in the specified quantity. The fixed animal offerings have a flexible grain component. <em>Vehin shemen la\'efah</em>: the oil portion consistently specified.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>uveyom hachodesh par ben-baqar tamim</strong> (\'and on the day of the new moon, a young bull without blemish\'): the New Moon offerings — a bull, six lambs, and a ram. The New Moon (Rosh Chodesh) is elevated to an occasion of substantial sacrifice alongside the Sabbath. <em>Sheishet kevasim ve\'ayil tamim yihyu</em>: the animal list. The New Moon as a covenant calendar marker is given structural importance in the new temple order.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>uminchah efah lapar</strong> (\'and a grain offering — an ephah for the bull\'): the proportionate grain offerings. The flexibility noted in v.5 — <em>matnat yado</em> for the lambs — reappears here. The prescribed quantities for bulls and rams are fixed; for lambs the grain offering is proportionate to what the prince can give. The freewill element within the regulated system balances obligation and devotion.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>uvebo hanasi derekh ulam hasha\'ar yavo</strong> (\'and when the prince enters, he shall enter by the vestibule of the gate\'): the specific path for the prince\'s entry and exit — always through the vestibule (<em>ulam</em>). <em>Uvedarko yetze\'</em> (\'and by the same way he shall go out\'): unlike the general worshippers (vv. 9-10) who enter one gate and exit another, the prince enters and exits by the same route — perhaps indicating his distinctive mediating role between the people and the sanctuary.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>uvevo am ha\'aretz lifnei YHWH bammo\'adim</strong> (\'when the people of the land come before YHWH at the appointed feasts\'): the one-directional flow rule for the people at festivals — entry through the north gate means exit through the south gate, and vice versa. <em>Yotze derekh-sha\'ar nagevu</em> (\'shall go out by the way of the south gate\'). The traffic management of worshippers prevents congestion and ensures orderly, reverent movement through sacred space. The directional regulation also has symbolic weight: forward movement through the sanctuary, not retreat.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>vehannasi betocham bevo\'am yavo uvetzetam yetze\'u</strong> (\'and the prince, among them — when they enter, he enters, and when they go out, he goes out\'): the prince as the representative member of the worshipping community. He does not precede or follow the people as a separate dignitary but moves with them (<em>betocham</em>, among them). The communal nature of the prince\'s worship is emphasized — he is the first among worshippers, not a separate liturgical class.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>uvachagim uva\'mo\'adim tihyeh hamincha efah lapar</strong> (\'and at festivals and at appointed feasts, the grain offering shall be an ephah for the bull\'): the festival grain-offerings specification repeated for the general festival context. The grain offerings follow the same structure as the specific festival prescriptions in chapter 45 — a unified system across all sacred occasions. <em>Matnat yado</em> for the lambs again — the freewill element in the lamb-grain offering preserved.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>uchi ya\'aseh hanasi nedavah</strong> (\'and when the prince makes a freewill offering\'): the freewill offering (<em>nedavah</em> — from <em>nadav</em>, to volunteer/give spontaneously) is specified separately from the required offerings. The east inner gate is opened specifically for the prince\'s freewill offering; after he exits the gate is closed again. The opening and closing of the gate for the freewill offering signals that spontaneous devotion, not merely calendar obligation, has its own access to the sacred space.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>keves ben-shnato tamim ta\'aseh olah laYHWH laboqer boqer</strong> (\'a lamb a year old without blemish you shall prepare as a burnt offering to YHWH morning by morning\'): the daily burnt offering — one lamb each morning, not the two lambs of Numbers 28:3-4. The evening offering (<em>tamid</em>) is omitted in Ezekiel\'s vision — only the morning daily. This has generated discussion: perhaps the vision is selective, emphasizing a continuous morning orientation toward YHWH rather than prescribing the complete Levitical daily rhythm.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>uminchah ta\'aseh alav baboqer</strong> (\'and a grain offering you shall prepare with it in the morning\'): the accompanying grain offering — a sixth of an ephah of fine flour (<em>solet</em>) with a third of a hin of oil. <em>Mincha tamid olat tamid laYHWH</em> (\'a continual grain offering, a continual burnt offering for YHWH\'): the <em>tamid</em> (continual) characterizes both offerings — the daily morning worship is perpetual, not occasional. The rhythm of <em>boqer boqer</em> (morning by morning) establishes the tempo of the new temple\'s liturgical life.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>ya\'asu et-hakeves ve\'et-hamminchah ve\'et-hashemen baboqer boqer</strong> (\'they shall prepare the lamb and the grain offering and the oil — morning by morning\'): the triple repetition of the morning-orientation confirms the continuous daily worship at the heart of the new temple order. The eschatological temple has a daily rhythm that is simple (one lamb), perpetual (<em>tamid</em>), and consistently oriented toward the morning — the beginning of each new day acknowledged as YHWH\'s gift.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>koh amar Adonai YHWH ki-yitten hanasi mattana la\'echad mivanav</strong> (\'thus says the Lord YHWH: if the prince gives a gift to any of his sons\'): the inheritance principle for the prince\'s land. Gifts to sons become their permanent inheritance (<em>achuztam hi birushasha lahem</em>). But gifts to servants can only be held until the jubilee year (<em>shnat haderut</em>), after which they revert. The jubilee principle from Leviticus 25 is maintained in the new order: land cannot be permanently alienated through servitude.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>ve\'im-yitten mattana me\'nachalato le\'echad me\'avadav</strong> (\'but if he gives a gift from his inheritance to one of his servants\'): the servant case. <em>Vehayetah lo ad-shnat haderut veshavah lanasi</em> (\'it shall be his until the year of release/jubilee and shall return to the prince\'): the jubilee reversion — the servant does not permanently acquire the prince\'s land. <em>Ach nachalato lava\'nav tihyeh lahem</em> (\'only his inheritance shall be for his sons to them\'): the prince\'s land is held in trust for his descendants, not permanently dispersible through gift to servants. This provision prevents the prince from accumulating or dispersing land in ways that destabilize the tribal land inheritance.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>velo-yiqach hanasi min-nachala ha\'am</strong> (\'and the prince shall not take from the people\'s inheritance\'): the direct prohibition on the Naboth\'s-vineyard type of royal confiscation. <em>Lehona\'am me\'achuzatam</em> (\'to oppress them out of their possession\'): <em>hona</em> (to oppress, especially economically) — the specific verb for the economic exploitation the Israelite kings regularly practiced. <em>Me\'achuztam</em> (\'from their possession\'): each family\'s ancestral land holding is protected from royal appropriation. The prince\'s portion is specified (45:7-8) precisely so he will not need to take from others.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>vayvi\'eni bemavo asher al-ketef hasha\'ar el-leshkot haQodesh</strong> (\'and he brought me through the entrance that was at the side of the gate into the priestly chambers\'): the vision guide brings Ezekiel to the temple kitchens. The two sets of kitchen facilities — for the priests (vv. 19-20) and for the Levitical servants (vv. 21-24) — reflect the two-tier sacred service structure of chapters 44-45.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>zeh hamaqom asher yevashelu sham hakohanim et-ha\'asham ve\'et-hachatta\'t</strong> (\'this is the place where the priests shall boil the guilt offering and the sin offering\'): the sacred kitchen where the priests\' portion of the guilt and sin offerings is cooked. <em>Veyafeu et-hammincha leBelti hotzi el-hechatzer hachitzona</em> (\'and where they shall bake the grain offering, in order not to bring them out to the outer court\'): the isolation principle — the offerings that belong to the priests must be cooked and eaten within the priestly zone. The holiness of the sacrificial food must not be allowed to \'sanctify the people\' by contact — the same principle as the garment-holiness of 44:19.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>vatze\'eni el-hechatzer hachitzona</strong> (\'and he brought me out to the outer court\'): transition from the priestly inner area to the outer court, where the Levitical servants\' kitchen facilities are located. Four corner areas in the outer court, each with a small enclosed court. <em>Bechot yot hechatzer chatzerot qetanot</em> (\'in the corners of the court were small courts\'): the four enclosed areas symmetrically placed.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>arba machzurot bearbaat pinnot hechatzer</strong> (\'four joined/enclosed courts in the four corners of the court\'): <em>machzurot</em> (enclosed/walled courts) — the small kitchen areas. <em>Arba\'im orech ushEloshim rochav midda achat learba\'tam</em> (\'forty long and thirty wide, one measure for all four\'): uniform size, symmetrical placement. The architectural regularity of the sacred space is a consistent feature of Ezekiel\'s temple vision — perfect symmetry expressing divine order.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>turo sav lahem saviv learba\'tam</strong> (\'a course of stone was around them for all four\'): the construction detail of the kitchen enclosures. <em>Umevushillot asuyot tachat haturim saviv</em> (\'and cooking-hearths made under the courses/ledges around\'): the cooking facilities built into the stone structure. The detail suggests functional kitchens fully integrated into the architectural plan — worship includes the physical preparation of food, and that preparation has its proper designated space.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>vayomer elai eleh beit hamevashllim asher yevashelu sham meshartei habayit et-zevach ha\'am</strong> (\'and he said to me: these are the houses of boiling where the servants of the house shall boil the sacrifice of the people\'): the Levitical servants cook the people\'s portions of the peace offerings here. The chapter — and the liturgical regulation section of the temple vision — closes with a picture of shared communal meal: priests eating their portions of sin and guilt offerings in the inner priestly kitchen, people\'s peace offerings cooked in the outer Levitical kitchen, the entire community sustained by the sacrificial system that YHWH has ordained. The temple is not merely a ritual performance space but a place of communal feasting in the presence of YHWH.</p>'
}
}

